  "prompt": "What is a good university for MS in mechanical engineering?",
  "response": "There are many excellent universities worldwide for pursuing a Master of Science (MS) in Mechanical Engineering. The best choice for you depends on factors like your academic profile, research interests, location preferences, and career goals. Here are some of the top universities globally for mechanical engineering:\n\n### **United States**\n1. **Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT)** - Renowned for cutting-edge research and innovation in engineering.\n2. **Stanford University** - Offers a strong focus on interdisciplinary research and entrepreneurship.\n3. **California Institute of Technology (Caltech)** - Known for its small class sizes and high-impact research.\n4. **University of California, Berkeley (UC Berkeley)** - Excellent for mechanical engineering, especially in areas like robotics and energy.\n5. **Georgia Institute of Technology (Georgia Tech)** - Strong in areas like aerospace, robotics, and manufacturing.\n6. **University of Michigan, Ann Arbor** - Known for its broad research opportunities and industry connections.\n7. **Purdue University** - Highly regarded for its engineering programs and research facilities.\n\n### **Europe**\n1. **ETH Zurich (Switzerland)** - One of the top engineering schools in Europe with a strong focus on research.\n2. **Technical University of Munich (TUM, Germany)** - Known for its engineering programs and industry collaborations.\n3. **Imperial College London (UK)** - Offers a cutting-edge curriculum and strong ties to industry.\n4. **KTH Royal Institute of Technology (Sweden)** - A leading technical university in Europe.\n5. **Delft University of Technology (Netherlands)** - Renowned for its engineering programs and research facilities.\n\n### **Canada**\n1. **University of Toronto** - One of the top engineering schools in Canada with a strong research focus.\n2. **University of Waterloo** - Known for its co-op programs and strong industry connections.\n3. **McGill University** - Offers a diverse and research-intensive environment.\n\n### **Asia**\n1. **National University of Singapore (NUS)** - A leading university in Asia with a strong engineering program.\n2. **Tsinghua University (China)** - Known for its engineering and technology programs.\n3. **Indian Institute of Technology (IITs, India)** - The IITs, especially IIT Bombay, IIT Delhi, and IIT Madras, are highly regarded for mechanical engineering.\n4. **KAIST (South Korea)** - A top engineering university in Asia with a strong focus on research and innovation.\n\n### **Australia**\n1. **University of Melbourne** - Known for its engineering programs and research opportunities.\n2. **University of New South Wales (UNSW)** - Offers a strong focus on innovation and industry connections.\n\n### **Key Considerations**\n- **Research Areas**: Look for universities that specialize in your area of interest (e.g., robotics, thermodynamics, materials science, automotive engineering).\n- **Faculty and Labs**: Check the faculty profiles and research labs to ensure alignment with your interests.\n- **Location and Cost**: Consider the cost of living, tuition fees, and potential scholarships.\n- **Rankings and Reputation**: Consult rankings like QS World University Rankings, Times Higher Education, and U.S. News & World Report.\n- **Alumni Network and Career Opportunities**: Look for universities with strong industry connections and career support.\n\nUltimately, the best university for you will depend on your specific goals and preferences. Make sure to research thoroughly and consider reaching out to current students or alumni for insights.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
